article.headline: Duffy comes to life in second half
article.linkText: Notre Dame busts BC for 10th straight win
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- Notre Dame (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP)  solved its poor outside
shooting with a few timely offensive rebounds.

Megan Duffy had all 14 of her points in the second half as the
Fighting Irish overcame an 11-point deficit to beat Boston
College (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 25 AP)  54-47 Tuesday night for their 10th straight victory.

Trailing 41-38 with just over five minutes to play, Notre Dame
came up empty on five straight possessions before pounding the
glass for key baskets.

Jacqueline Batteast, who led the Fighting Irish with 15 points,
cut it to 41-40 with the first of three baskets coming from
offensive rebounds in the closing 5:23.

"I just tried to keep going by being more aggressive," said
Batteast, who made 6-of-17 shots from the floor against constant
double teams. "I can't stop shooting."

Charel Allen's putback made it 42-41 after a BC turnover, but
the Eagles regained the lead on Kathrin Ress' foul-line jumper.

Duffy's two free throws gave the Irish the lead for good at
44-43 with 2:22 to go. Allen's baseline drive pushed Notre Dame's
edge to three points.

The Eagles closed to 46-45 on Lisa Macchia's layup with 1:08 to
go, but Teresa Borton's offensive rebound and layup off a
desperation 3-point attempt by Duffy made it 48-45 with 33 seconds
remaining.

"I think we allowed a few rebounds inside and we rushed some
shots," BC coach Cathy Inglese said.

Notre Dame holds a one-game lead over Rutgers and Connecticut
atop the Big East. The Fighting Irish (23-3, 11-2) play at Rutgers (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) on Saturday.

Notre Dame shot just 34.5 percent in the game (19-for-55).

"This week is just huge and this was such an important game for
us going into the Rutgers game," Notre Dame coach Muffet McGraw
said. "Rutgers is a battle for first place, but this was really
the more important game; one we really had to win to stay the
course we're on."

The Eagles (16-7, 7-5) dropped to 0-6 this season against ranked
opponents. Clare Droesch paced BC with 10 points.

"We played a great game tonight, but the two minutes we didn't
hurt us," Droesch said.

Duffy hit four free throws and Breona Gray two in the closing 24
seconds to secure the victory.

After Notre Dame sliced an 11-point halftime deficit to six, BC
opened a 39-28 lead on Aja Parham's baseline jumper with 13:51
left. But the Irish scored 12 of the next 14 points, cutting it to
41-40 on Batteast's putback with 5:23 to play.

BC went 10:01 without a basket after Parham's hoop.

The Eagles held the Irish to their lowest scoring half of the
season, taking a 26-15 edge at the break. BC held Notre Dame to
21.7-percent shooting from in the half (5-of-23), mainly
double-teaming leading scorer Batteast nearly every time she
touched the ball in the low post to disrupt the offensive rhythm.

BC has dropped four of five games since leading scorer Jessalyn
Deveny was lost for the season with a ruptured right Achilles
tendon.

Notre Dame improved to 7-2 against ranked opponents and 10-1 on
the road.
